                        "description": "Metabolites were identified using NIST05 software (http://www.nist.gov/srd/mslist.htm) and the mass spectral and retention time index (RI) collection of the Golm metabolome database [1][2]. Mass spectral matching was manually checked, and accepted with thresholds of match >650 (maximum 1000) and RI < 1.0 %. RIs represent Kov\u00e0ts indices [3] calculated from additions of C12, C15, C19, C22, C32, C36n-alkanes. Table S4 lists not only metabolites identified by standard addition but also mass spectral tags that are as yet unidentified [4].\n</p>\nRef:</br>\n[1] J. Kopka, N. Schauer, S. Krueger, C. Birkemeyer, B. Usadel, E. Bergmueller, P. Doermann, W. Weckwerth, Y. Gibon, M. Stitt, L. Willmitzer, A. R. Fernie and D. Steinhauser (2005) GMD@CSB.DB: the Golm Metabolome Database, Bioinformatics 21: 1635-1638. PMID:15613389</br>\n[2] N. Schauer, D. Steinhauser, S. Strelkov, D. Schomburg, G. Allison, T. Moritz, K. Lundgren, U. Roessner-Tunali, M. G. Forbes, L. Willmitzer, A. R. Fernie and J. Kopka (2005) GC-MS libraries for the rapid identification of metabolites in complex biological samples, FEBS Letters 579: 1332-1337. PMID:15733837</br>\n[3] Kovats, E.S. (1958) Gas-chromatographische Charakterisierung organischer Verbindungen: Teil 1. Retentionsindices aliphatischer Halogenide, Alkohole, Aldehyde und Ketone. Helv. Chim. Acta, 41, 1915\u20131932.</br>\n[4] G. G. Desbrosses, J. Kopka and M. K. Udvardi (2005) Lotus japonicus metabolic profiling. Development of gas chromatography-mass spectrometry resources for the study of plant-microbe interactions, Plant Physiology 137: 1302-1318. PMID: 15749991</br>",
